But of course, I do believe that if a player, any player, enjoys something, there is some validity in it. It's our jobs as designers isn't it, to give people experiences they like and enjoy. There's no one correct answer.

Anyway, rambling on because over the years I became really tired out of open world games and I wasn't sure what it was that made me feel that way. It was the flood of map markings. They took the exploration element away and I got BORED.

Sea of Thieves actually middle-grounds on this really well, come to think. You make the marks yourself, after identifying the island on a map. And when you get there (if an X marks the spot) you have to read clues to find.

And so when people speak of no map markers making for unfriendly design, I wholeheartedly disagree. It's design that compliments the rest of the quest/world design, and I think games are better for having more than one "template" way in which open world's are designed.

Finding the place you need to reach, in my mind, is a gameplay experience in itself. If it's marked out for you, the "finding" isn't a part of the experience. The physical journey, sure. But no finding.
Optional map markers probably wouldn't work either because as I said, if a game is built and designed with map marker-ing in mind, that just wouldn't work out.

It's like joining all the dots for me. You're just sending me on a route to complete an activity in another area. I know everything between here and there because it's all marked out. I can't feel surprised or like I'm having an adventure.

I don't like map markers because if a game is built around having them, that's a whole chunk of exploration/mystery gameplay that just doesn't exist. If you tell me where everything is, how am I going to have fun finding anything? I'm not.
